Let’s consider the expression $\frac{3}{206}+\frac{9}{2\cdot103^2}+\frac{27}{2\cdot103^3}+\cdots$. The denominator is $206$ times $103$. The sum can be written as \begin{align*} \frac{3}{206}+\frac{9}{2\cdot103^2}+\frac{27}{2\cdot103^3}+\cdots&=\frac{3}{206}\left[1+\frac{3}{2\cdot103}+\left(\frac{3}{2\cdot103}\right)^2+\cdots\right]\\ &=\frac{3}{206}\left[\frac{1}{1-\frac{3}{2\cdot103}}\right] \\ &=\frac{3}{206} \cdot \frac{2\cdot103}{2\cdot103-3} \\ &=\frac{3}{206} \cdot \frac{206}{203} \\ &=\boxed{\frac{3}{203}} \\ &=0.014799 \\ &= 0.0147 \boxed{9} \end{align*}
So the infinite series $\frac{3}{206}+\frac{9}{2\cdot103^2}+\frac{27}{2\cdot103^3}+\cdots$ has only one digit after the decimal point.
